label_categories.field_description:
Which refrigerator is suitable for me?
Find the answer with the energy label.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new refrigerator? These checklists help you.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choosing the right energy class
  • Find out, in which energy class the most saving appliances are!
Choosing the right climate class
  • Climate class N (Normal) for appliances in the living area
  • Climate class SN (Sub-normal) for appliances in cool rooms like cellars
Checking the sound level
  • 30 decibels correspond to whispering
  • More than 40 decibels are not recommendable

field_checklist_entries.text: Built-in: saves room and is integrated in the kitchen unit
Freestanding: can be taken along when moving house
1 person (about 120 liter)
2 persons (about 160 liter)
3 persons (about 200 liter)
4 persons (about 250 liter)
Yes (choose a separate freezer compartment with a separate door which consumes less energy compared to an integrated one.)
No, not necessary
Temperature scale with accuracy of one degree
Warning signal if the temperature is too high or the door is open
No frost function (no need to defrost the freezer)
Zero degree zone (preserves fresh foods for longer)

label_tips.field_description: The cooler the environment, the less your fridge has to work. Do not place it next to the heating or the stove and neither in the blazing sun.
Some space between the wall and the refrigerator and regularly cleaned ventilation grilles prevent heat accumulation.
label_tips.field_information_text: The back of the refrigerator conducts the heat of the foodstuff outward. In case of heat accumulation, the appliance does not work properly any longer – and catches fire at worst.

label_tips.field_description:
Caution: Not all foodstuffs feel good in the refrigerator!
  • Tomatoes lose their taste there
  • Bananas get brown spots
  • Avocados prefer post-ripening at room temperature
  • Citrus fruits like lemons do not tolerate cold
Defrost your appliance once or twice a year. This reduces electricity consumption enormously.
label_tips.field_information_text:
Ice has an insultating effect, the generated cold is hindered to get to the interior. This consumes a lot of energy.
Even a 1-centimeter layer of ice doubles the electricity consumption of the freezer compartment.

label_tips.field_description:
When you are gone on a journey, also allow your refrigerator a vacation. Empty it before, defrost and clean it – and then leave it open.

Successful defrost:
  1. Switch off the appliance, take the foodstuffs out and keep it in a cool place
  2. Take out shelves and compartments
  3. Place towels and cloth on the floor in front of the refrigerator
  4. Place a pot filled with hot water into the fridge and close the door
  5. After 20 minutes remove defrosted ice with a wooden spoon or a plastic scraper carefully
  6. Wipe with dishwashing detergent or diluted vinegar

label_category_guide.field_intro: If you use the climate zone in the refrigerator correctly, you save energy and the foodstuffs stay fresh for longer. Look where your foodstuff feels best!
label_category_guide.field_outro: Some refrigerators have a different division or additional compartments, therefore also pay attention to the manual!
label_category_guide.field_information_text: Many new refrigerators have a dynamic cooling. In this case, a fan spreads the cold air. As a result, the temperature is the same everywhere in the refrigerator and you und you can put your foodstuff wherever you like.

fridge_left_info_zones.field_tooltip: Main compartment: Cooked dishes like cake and sauces
Main compartment: fish or meets that spoil quickly
Main compartment: salad, fruit and vegetables

fridge_right_info_zones.field_tooltip: Door: drink (except milk, it's not cold enough here)

label_categories.field_description: Which dishwasher is suitable for you? Which tips help to simplify dishwashing? Here you find the answers.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new dishwasher? The checklist helps you when buying one.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choosing the right energy class
  • Find out, in which energy class the most saving appliances are!
Pay attention to the power consumption
  • For appliances with 14 place settings 67 kWh per 100 cycles is a very good value.
  • For appliances with 10 place settings 66 kWh per 100 cycles is a very good value.
Check the water consumption
  • 10 litres or less per cycle is very good

label_category_checklists.field_title: How broad should the dishwascher be?

field_checklist_entries.text: 60 cm width: for households with 3 persons or more, efficient power and water consumption
45 cm width: reasonable with little space and a small household
Built-in: is integrated under the worktop
Freestanding: can be taken along when moving house
Extra quiet (for open kitchens)
Child protection
Preselection of start time
Cutlery drawer

label_tips.field_description: Who always only uses his favourite plate cannot fill the dishwasher. But only full means washing the dishes efficiently.
label_tips.field_information_text: Dishwashers with a width of 60 cm are most efficient regarding energy and water consumption. They can also be reasonable for smaller household if more tableware is used.

label_tips.field_description: Dispose of coarse food scraps in the bin. Otherwise they block sieves and pumps.
You do not need to prerinse glasses or plates by hand. This consumes water, energy and detergent unnecessarily.
label_tips.field_information_text: When washing the dishes, most of the energy is needed to heat the water. The dishwasher uses less water than washing dishes by hand – and is therefore more favourable. A modern appliance consumes about 10 l of water for a full load of dishes and less than 1 kWh of energy – washing the dishes by hand needs about twice as much for the same amount of dishes.

label_tips.field_description: Dishes only become clean, when the water reaches all surfaces. Putting the dishes into the appliance carefully avoids a second cycle.
In the eco programme, the wash cycle is longer, but at lower temperatures. This saves energy and money.
label_tips.field_information_text: From time to time you should choose the highest temperature. This removes grease residues, which could block the appliance.

label_categories.field_description: Which washing machine is suitable for you? Which tips help to simplify washing? Here you find the answers.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new washing machine? The checklist helps you when buying one.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choosing the right energy class
  • Find out in which energy class the most saving appliances are!
These special functions are useful
  • Aquastop
  • Short programme
  • Pause button

label_category_checklists.field_title: How many persons use the washing machine?

field_checklist_entries.text: 1-2 persons (5-7 kg capacity recommended)
3-4 persons (7-8 kg)
5+ persons (8 kg or more)
Front loader (mostly 50 to 60 cm width): Opening in the front, there are also built-in appliances
Top loader (45 cm width or smaller): Opening on top, saves space
Preselection of time
Load detection with dosage recommendation
Automatic load control (saves power and water if the drum is not full)

label_tips.field_description: Choose an appliance wih the appropriate capacity for your household.
label_tips.field_information_text: The machine is more efficient if it runs full. Buy an appliance which you can use fully loaded as often as possible. The machine is full if you have to put in the last pieces of laundry with slight pressure.

label_tips.field_description: Coloured and white laundry can be washed together in the "Eco 40-60" programme wihout occurence of a grey veil on the white laundry.
Also with hard water, the quantity recommended for hardness level 1 is sufficient.
label_tips.field_information_text: Moreover: Use heavy-duty detergents only for white and resistant laundry. It contains bleaching agents to remove spots and yellowing - but also bleaches colours.

label_tips.field_description: The "Eco 40-60" program is the star of the washing cycles. Although it takes more time – it saves a lot of energy and water.
label_tips.field_information_text: The eco programme takes longer but this has less impact on the costs than the temperature.

label_tips.field_description:
The short programmes of many washing machines consume a lot of energy. If you need to wash fast, simply reduce the washing temperature: In modern machines coloured and white laundry will be cleaned properly at temperatures from 20 °C to 40 °C.
Thanks to new technology and detergents the priciple "one level colder" is generally recommended for almost all laundry: Choose one temperature level colder than given on the care label.

label_categories.field_description: Which tumble dryer is suitable for you? Which tips help to simplify tumble-drying? Here you find the answers.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new tumble dryer? This checklist helps you when buying one.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choosing the right energy class
  • Find out in which energy class energy class the most saving appliances are!
  • Appliances in the most efficent energy class are usually equipped with heat pump technology.
Useful functions
  • A model with moisture dependent control is more energy-saving and gentle than a time-controlled model.
  • The standard cotton programme is particularly energy efficient.
  • In the automatic programme, sensors check the moisture and regulate the programme duration.
  • Short programmes are only suitable for slightly moist laundry.
Checking the sound level
  • In a flat, the sound level of the tumble dryer should be less than 65 dezibels. This corresponds to the loudness of a normal conversation. In a cellar, it is not a problem to have a louder appliance.

field_checklist_entries.text: Heat pump tumble dryer: high energy efficiency, higher purchase price
Condenser tumble dryer: intermediate energy efficiency, intermediate purchase price
Vented tumble dryer: poor energy efficiency, low purchase price
1-2 persons (7 kg capacity recommended)
3-4 persons (8 kg)
5 and more persons (9 kg or more)
Front loader (60 cm width): Opening in the front, there are also built-in appliances
Top loader (45 cm width): Opening on top, saves space

label_tips.field_description: Heat pump tumble dryers are only a little more expensive but save more than 50 % of the energy that a conventional condenser tumble dryer consumes.
Spinning the laundry in the washing machine with 1400 instead of 1000 revolutions per minute saves up to 40 % energy when drying it in the tumble dryer.
You can save energy by choosing the right programme: "Standard cotton" is particulary energy efficient, "Automatic" automatically stops the programme when the laundry is dry.
label_tips.field_information_text: You wish to iron the laundry afterwards? Then the programme "ironing dry" saves time and energy.

label_tips.field_description: Clean the fluff filter after each use. A blocked filter prolongs the drying time – and consumes more energy.
When there is a lack of space, the tumble dryer can be put on the washing machine.
label_tips.field_information_text: When stacking the appliances, the tumble dryer may have a lower capacity than the washing machine. Because not every piece of laundry which was in the washing machine is also suited for the dryer.

label_categories.field_description: Which LED lamp is suitable for you? Which tips help to create the right lighting atmosphere? Here you find the answers.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new LED lamp? The checklist helps you when buying one.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choosing the right energy class
  • Find out in which energy class the most efficient lamps are!
Checking the energy consumption
  • For a 470 lumens lamp, 6 kWh per 1000 hours is a good value.
  • For a 800 lumens lamp, 8 kWh is a good value.
  • For a 1500 lumens lamp, 16 kWh is a good value.
Make sure to buy a product with a long lifetime
  • The lifetime given on the package should at least be 20.000 hours (or 20 years).
Choose the appropriate socket
  • Not every LED lamp fits into every socket. The variaty is large. Take your old lamp with you into the store to find the appropriate variant for your luminaire.

label_category_checklists.field_title: How bright should the lamp be?

field_checklist_entries.text: 470 lumens (suitable for example for reading lights)
800 lumens (comfortable light for living rooms)
1.500 lumens (very bright light, for example for working spaces)
Warm white for living rooms and bedrooms
Neutral white for the office, kitchen and bathroom
Daylight white for the workshop and the bathroom mirror

label_category_checklists.field_title: Would you like to dim your lamp?

field_checklist_entries.text: Yes
No

label_tips.field_description: LED lamps are absolute energy professionals: they consume up to 90 % less energy than comparable incandescent lamps. This is noticeable on the electricity bill! And they have a longer lifetime: an average LED lamp which is burning 2.75 hours daily lasts about 15 years.
Choose the appropriate lamp shape! Bulb, teardrop shape or spotlight – some of the most popular types that each create a special atmosphere and fit different lampshade designs.

Before you buy a lamp, decide which kind of atmosphere you want to create. Not every lamp is suitable for cosy situations. Some have a cold light color which is better for the office or workshop. The lamp's packaging has information on light color.

Find out which socket your lamp should have before shopping. It has to fit the lampholder in your luminaire. The socket is the bottom part of the lamp that oes into the lampholder first. Most common socket types are E27, E14, GU10, GU9, GU5.3, GU4 and G4. You can take the old lamp to the shop to find a similar replacement with the same socket.

Vocabulary for lamp shopping: The outer part is called luminaire. It consists of a lampshade with a lampholder inside and any other decorative and technical parts -  except the actual lamp. In colloquial terms often both is called a lamp. Whether you hear the word bulb, light etc. – the official term for the part giving the light is simple: lamp.

label_categories.field_description: Which is the right TV set for you? What do you need to know to make watching even more fun? The answers are here.

label_category_checklist_data.field_intro: You need a new television set? This checklist helps you when buying one.
label_category_checklist_data.field_information_text:
Choose the right energy efficiency class
  • Find out in which energy class the most efficint TVs are at this moment!
Compare electricity consumption
  • Compare electricty consumption for 1000 hours in kWh of the TV models you are interested in. In doing so, you get an overview of the energy costs.

label_category_checklists.field_title: What kind of TV would you like?

field_checklist_entries.text: LED: good brightness and value for money
OLED: very thin and light, high-quality picture, more expensive

label_category_checklists.field_title: How big should your screen be?

field_checklist_entries.text: 82 cm / 32 inch (recommended for 2 m viewing distance from the TV)
102 cm / 40 inch (sufficient for distance 3 m)
127+ cm / 50+ inch (for large rooms with 4 m and more viewing distance)
Sensor for ambient light
Motion sensor
Quick start function
3D ready

label_tips.field_description: Choose a TV that is not bigger than necessary.
label_tips.field_information_text: The bigger your TV's screen size (diagonal), the more energy it uses. The diagonal should be about a third of the distance between the TV and the viewer. If you sit quite close to the device (1.5 m) a small screen (50 cm diagonal) is sufficient.

label_tips.field_description: Check that your TV has a built-in receiver for the programmes you want to watch. This can save money compared to a receiver you have to buy seperately.
label_tips.field_information_text:
Not sure which TV signal is available at your home? Ask your landlord.
The most common technologies are digital signals via antenna (DVB-T2), cable (DVB-C) and satellite (DVB-S). Those are integrated in most modern TV sets.

label_tips.field_description: Some additional functions like 3D or quick start use extra electricity.
label_tips.field_information_text: Many TVs have an ambient light that increases energy use. You can deactivate it when it is not needed.

label_tips.field_description: Choose a spot without direct sunlight hitting the display. If you increase the brightness to fight the sunlight, the electricity consumptions increases, too.
label_tips.field_information_text: Some TVs have an ambient light sensor. It adapts the brightness of the picture. This can save energy, provided the room is not to well lighted.

label_tips.field_description: Dozing off or walking off when watching? A sleep timer or motion sensor can save energy by switching off the TV when nobody is watching.
